ed in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]},{"name":"Georgi","meanings":["From Greek <i>Georgios</i>.  See  <b>George</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alba","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":[", occasionally used in the English-speaking world. It appears to be from the feminine form of the Latin adjective <i>albus</i>, but may rather be a derivative of Germanic <i>alb</i> ‘elf, supernatural being’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Guri of Alba was born in 1012, in Scotland. She had at least 2 daughters with Andlaw Fitz Hemming of France. She died in Somme, Picardie, France."},"et":{"1012–":"1012–Surnud","1010–Male":"1010–Surnud","1040–1100":"1040–1100","1054–1088":"1054–1088","1012–Female":"1012–Surnud","1012":"1012","1100":"1100","1088":"1088","1054":"1054","1010":"1010","1040":"1040","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Alba":"Scotland","Europe":"Europe","Somme, Nord Pas-de-Calais, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1012–":"10